second of which will surprise some people:<br>
<br>
1)As is commonly said of fusion, the waste products are much more manageable than those of fission.  Instead of plutonium and uranium and about 240 other radioactive waste products, the key wastes from fusion would be Helium or neutrons and then the secondary byproducts.<br>
<br>
2)The binding energy per nucleon is what yields energy production.  Looked at as a trend of Bind Energy per nucleon VS Atomic Mass Number, you can see that it varies much more exponentially with low mass numbers than high mass numbers.  Put into plain english-The energy yield from equivalent numbers of reactions, fusion vs fission, would be much higher for fusion.  Exponentially so, in fact.  This means you need less fusion reactions, and thus even less waste, to produce the same amounts of power.  Of course this will neccessitate a finer control of the reaction, especially with masses being much smaller and finite to measure changes in, but these are all workable things. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   With the smaller masses, and also fewer reactions needed, we're talking about &quot;reactors&quot; that would be maybe 1% of the size of current ones.  Incredible thought,eh?  Take a current nuclear site and it could house perhaps 20 or 30 fusion reactors instead of a single fission reactor.  Or, spread out fusion reactors all over, and have more localized power grid that could also draw on other power grids for stability.  And that's just commercial.  For space ships, the difference in mass and size would be even more advantageous, especially if fusion and antimatter were used for dual reactions, which is what NASA is looking to do.<br>
<br>
<br>
