<br>
:clears his throat:  Uhm, wrong.  While I agree that Pu-239 is a common byproduct of nuclear fission in commercial reactors, it is not the same thing as making it a Power Breeder Reactor, such as the Savannah River facility.  The Pu-239 that is produced within a commercial reactor is a design element, whereby a fertile species (U-239 blanket) and a fissile species(U-235 enrichment region of fuel) through fission and a serious of nuclear processes(neutron capture and a couple beta decays) yield Pu-239, which is a fissile species.  Thus, as the fuel cycle continues and U-235 is burned up, Pu-239 is made to replace it.  0 power comes from Pu-239 in the beginning of a fuel cycle, but significant portions(above 30%,if i remember the diagram correctly...I'm unsure on exact number tho) come from Pu-239 towards the end as U-235 becomes less effective as a fissile source.<br>
<br>
Commercial reactors are not used as &quot;bopmb factories&quot;, and have never been.  There is a very big different between DoE/DoD facilities like Savannah River, which is a Power Breeder reactor that produces power and is used to breed Pu-239, and commercial facilities that are Converter Reactors.  Please also note that commercial facilities are light-water moderated, whilest breeders are generally heavy-water moderated.<br>
<br>
As far as nuclear activity...new plants are going to be built by 2010.  Bush has already made the US policy.  In addition, there are 2 plants nationally where construction is being resumed, having been previously stopped years ago.  These plants will go operational within the next few years. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=brucetrib>brucetrib</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/23/02 9:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=300.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: So much for atomic power...au contrairer better nukes </span><hr size=1> Better nuke in the future...<br>
